  "context_summary": "9-month-old child brought in with 4 days of high fever followed by a blotchy red rash that began at the hairline and behind the ears and is now spreading down onto the trunk. For the 3 days before the rash the child had a worsening cough, runny nose, and red watery eyes. The family returned from international travel to visit relatives 10 days ago. The child is miserable and feeding poorly but maintaining airway and hydration. The doctor has established the cephalocaudal rash progression and the preceding respiratory-and-conjunctival prodrome.",
  "good_next_question": "Is the child up to date on their vaccinations, including the MMR?",
  "rationale": "This question tests vaccination status, the single largest prior-shifter for measles and the discriminator that separates it from the benign fever-and-rash pile (nonspecific viral exanthem, roseola, drug rash) the presentation otherwise pattern-matches to. The prodrome already fits measles textbook-perfectly — the three C's (cough, coryza, conjunctivitis) preceding a rash that descends from the hairline downward — but a clinician anchored on 'common viral rash' can explain all of that away without ever revising the prior. Susceptibility is what moves measles from rare to live candidate: at 9 months the child is below the routine first-dose age (typically given at 12 months), so unless an early dose was given before travel the child is unimmunized, and recent international travel to visit relatives is a classic importation route. International travel in an infant under 12 months is precisely the situation in which an accelerated MMR dose should have been discussed, making a delayed-or-absent dose plus exposure a genuine susceptibility-plus-exposure setup. A positive answer (an early travel dose was given) lowers measles probability and lets the workup stay in the benign-viral lane; a gap raises measles sharply and triggers immediate airborne isolation, public-health notification, and a targeted exam for Koplik spots — though those buccal lesions are pathognomonic, they are an examination finding rather than something elicited by history and have often already faded once the rash appears, so they cannot be relied on as the pivot. This question beats further characterizing the rash because susceptibility, not morphology, is what most decisively reorders the differential and changes infection-control actions.",
  "tags": [
